I'm not sure the best way to do this. But this helps
```julia
julia> _tuple(x, ::Val{N}) where {N} = ((x[i] for i in 1:N)...,);

julia> _Tuple(x) = length(x) < 33 ? _tuple(x, Val(length(x))) : (collect(x)...,)

julia> x = 1:30;

julia> @btime _Tuple($x);
  198.715 ns (2 allocations: 288 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple($x);
  687.428 ns (2 allocations: 560 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple(1:32);
  734.733 ns (2 allocations: 608 bytes)

julia> @btime _Tuple(1:32);
  0.020 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)

julia> x = 1:34;

julia> @btime Tuple($x);
  764.595 ns (2 allocations: 624 bytes)

julia> @btime _Tuple($x);
  768.645 ns (2 allocations: 624 bytes)
```

Similar methods for `StepRange` and `StepRangeLen` also work for `Int` and `Float64` parameters. But, I don't know about other parameter types or `OrdinalRange`, which is the least common supertype.

