```julia
julia> @btime myTuple(1:100);
  5.495 μs (104 allocations: 6.25 KiB)

julia> @btime _Tuple(1:100);
  2.063 μs (2 allocations: 1.67 KiB)
```

But, to be clear: using `_Tuple` above, with `_tuple(x, ::Val{N})` is, in some cases, better than both `(s...,)` and `(collect(s)...,)`. You can verify this by testing. That's the only reason I used `_tuple(x, ::Val{N})`.

This is what I was thinking: What's the most efficient way to turn an iterator into a `Tuple`? Often, you see `(itr...,)`. In other code, often library code, for example `Base.Tuple`, you see `(collect(itr)...,)`.  So which is better?  The difference between the two can be large.

Here is a partial answer.
```julia
_Tuple1(x) = length(x) < 33 ? (x...,) : (collect(x)...,)
```
Then you get this
```julia
julia> @btime _Tuple1(1:32);
  0.020 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple(1:32);
  723.979 ns (2 allocations: 608 bytes)

julia> @btime _Tuple1(1:50);
  1.167 μs (2 allocations: 944 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple(1:50);
  1.080 μs (2 allocations: 944 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple(1.0:2.0:41.0);
  753.873 ns (23 allocations: 736 bytes)

julia> @btime _Tuple1(1.0:2.0:41.0);
  0.020 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple(1.0:2.0:71.0);
  1.286 μs (38 allocations: 1.22 KiB)

julia> @btime _Tuple1(1.0:2.0:71.0);
  1.281 μs (38 allocations: 1.22 KiB)
```
Great. So just use `_Tuple1` instead of `Tuple` for everything. But, actually `_Tuple1` is often worse.
For example you would need a method for `::Array`, no matter what length, to do just `(a...,)`, because `collect` will make a copy. `Tuple` already has this method.

You also have this for three dictionary keys:
```julia
julia> kd = keys(Dict(zip(1:3,1:3)));

julia> @btime _Tuple1($kd);
239.581 ns (5 allocations: 144 bytes)

julia> @btime Tuple($kd);
  163.017 ns (2 allocations: 112 bytes)
```
probably because the length of the iterator is not available. So keys should always be collected.

Finally, going back the first case I was trying to improve, if the range is not literal, there is no advantage:
```julia

julia> @btime Tuple(1:31);
  702.521 ns (2 allocations: 560 bytes)

julia> @btime _Tuple1(1:31);
  0.020 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)

julia> s = collect(1:31);

julia> @btime Tuple($s);
  670.259 ns (1 allocation: 256 bytes)

julia> @btime _Tuple1($s);
  667.285 ns (1 allocation: 256 bytes)
```
This is why I introduced the more complicated version above with `_tuple(x, ::Val{N})`. This is three times faster for `s=collect(1:31)`:
```julia
julia> @btime _Tuple($s);
  196.539 ns (1 allocation: 256 bytes)

julia> @btime ($s...,);  # And to be clear that splatting is not best
  673.942 ns (1 allocation: 256 bytes)
```

I'm doubtful that a maze of special cases in Base is the way to go. You'd need good benchmark tests, over a (well chosen) variety  of tests. And I guess the results will change as the compiler changes. Maybe if someone were ambitious, a package with a function that has optimal methods would be useful.


